963
Your Honor,

I, David Lambert, a 55-year-old individual with a clean criminal record up until this point, am here today to plead guilty to the charge of driving whilst disqualified.

I want to express my deepest remorse and regret for my actions. Just two months ago, I was rightfully disqualified from driving due to multiple speeding incidents. However, I unfortunately made the ill-considered choice to get behind the wheel and drive to a supermarket, completely oblivious to the fact that I was not allowed to do so according to the court's order.

I am truly ashamed of my lack of judgment and the disregard I showed for the court's previous decision. I want to assure the court that my intentions were not malicious, but rather, an unfortunate oversight on my part. It was an inexcusable mistake on my behalf, and I feel sincerely sorry for the trouble and inconvenience it has caused.

Realizing the severity of my offense, I am fully committed to taking the necessary steps to rectify my behavior and ensure that such a lapse in judgment will never occur again. I am willing to enroll in any appropriate courses or programs that the court deems necessary for my rehabilitation, and I am open to any means to make amends and compensate for the harm I have caused.

I recognize that my decision to plead guilty serves as a mitigating factor, as it demonstrates my acceptance of responsibility. I am fully aware of the consequences of my actions and the impact it has on society.

I humbly request the court's leniency and consideration for my genuine efforts to improve myself and make amends. I assure the court that this experience has profoundly taught me a valuable lesson, and I am fully committed to becoming a law-abiding citizen once again.

Thank you for your attention.

Sincerely,
David Lambert
